<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level CREATE ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_agent` UNCONDITIONAL create access
    on the `x_[scope]_case_task` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]`. This is the CREATE companion to the sibling READ ACL at
    ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml and the WRITE ACL at
    ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml; together with the
    case_manager-specific ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_manager.xml, the
    case_task-table create-permission set is fully and exhaustively realized
    for the three scoped roles (manager: yes; agent: yes; viewer: deny-by-
    default).

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - case_agent row, mirrored at the case_task
        table level per AAP Section 0.5.1 row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_[scope]_case_task_*.xml"
        ("Mirror ACL pattern at task level; case_agent can write only tasks
         where parent case is 'Assigned only'"):
            | Role                  | Create | Read              | Write             | Delete |
            | x_[scope]_case_agent  |  Yes   | Yes Assigned only | Yes Assigned only |  No    |
        This file authors the single "Create = Yes" cell of that row for the
        case_task table. The "Yes Assigned only" Read cell is authored by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_read_agent_assigned.xml; the "Yes Assigned
        only" Write cell by
        ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_write_agent_assigned.xml; the "No" Delete
        cell is enforced by the deliberate ABSENCE of any
        x_[scope]_case_task_delete_agent.xml file (ServiceNow record-level
        ACLs are deny-by-default: a role with no granting ACL for an
        operation cannot perform that operation). Each row of the ACL matrix
        maps to exactly one or zero ACL XML files; this per-cell granularity
        is what lets the Update Set add or remove role privileges
        independently without entangling roles or operations.
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) - all-roles create coverage on case_task:
          - case_manager: Create=Yes  -> ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_manager.xml
          - case_agent:   Create=Yes  -> THIS FILE
          - case_viewer:  Create=No   -> deliberate absence of any ACL
        Together these three facts implement the AAP's case_task creation
        contract: both managers and agents can author task records, but the
        lowest-privilege viewer (audit / compliance / supervisor tier)
        cannot.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 - ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced - case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
           cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The clause "case_agent cannot access UNASSIGNED cases" applies to
        read and write only - it is logically inapplicable to create
        because a record cannot be "assigned" to anyone before it exists.
        Therefore this ACL grants create unconditionally to any caller
        holding the x_[scope]_case_agent role; downstream visibility of
        and edits to the created task record are governed by the
        read/write _agent_assigned siblings, which DO restrict access to
        rows whose parent case is "Assigned only" to the calling user.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications - Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level CREATE binding for the mid-tier
        scoped role on the task domain.
      - Section 0.1.2 (Technical Interpretation - Access-control
        transformation): The ServiceNow target replaces
        ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.getRolesToPrivileges() (a
        Map<String, List<Object>> bound from application.rolesToPrivileges
        configuration) and AcmPluginUrlPrivilege URL-method enforcement
        with declarative scoped record-level ACLs. This XML record is
        therefore the declarative equivalent of the conceptual
        (case_agent, CREATE on TASK) cell of that ArkCase map.
      - Section 0.5.5 (State-Machine Transition Map): the In Progress -> 
        Resolved transition is gated by the rule "All linked
        x_[scope]_case_task records have status = Closed" with the verbatim
        blocking-error message "All tasks must be closed before resolving
        this case." For an agent to drive a case to Resolved, they must be
        able to AUTHOR the task records that get marked Closed - this ACL
        is what permits that authoring. Without this CREATE ACL, the agent
        role would have no path to insert task rows, the Resolved transition
        would be perpetually unreachable on agent-owned cases, and the
        end-to-end agent-driven case lifecycle defined in AAP Sections 0.5.5
        and 0.7.4 ("Cases created, assigned, progressed through all defined
        states, and closed via both internal UI and external portal") would
        be impossible to demonstrate.
      - Section 0.7.4 (Other User-Provided Rules) - "Tasks created, linked
        to cases, assigned, and closed - case resolution blocked until all
        linked tasks are closed." This success-criterion bullet implies
        that authenticated case_agent users must be able to create tasks
        on cases assigned to them via the internal native form view (the
        primary task-authoring surface for agents). THIS ACL is what makes
        that path permitted.
      - Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping Verbatim) - case_task schema:
            | Field        | Type                      | Constraints                  |
            | case         | Reference -> x_[scope]_case | Mandatory                  |
            | subject      | String(255)               | Mandatory                    |
            | type         | Choice                    | Investigation, Review, ...   |
            | status       | Choice                    | Open, In Progress, Closed    |
            | assigned_to  | Reference -> sys_user     | Mandatory                    |
            | due_date     | Date                      | Mandatory                    |
        Note that case_task does NOT carry its own assigned_group /
        assigned_agent fields - the "Assigned only" predicate from the
        AAP's matrix is therefore evaluated against the PARENT CASE row
        (referenced via current.case) by the read/write _agent_assigned
        siblings. For CREATE this dereference is irrelevant because no
        current row exists pre-insert; this is the second reason CREATE
        is unconditional (in addition to "current is null pre-insert").

    Why <advanced>false</advanced> (in contrast to read/write _agent_assigned):
      The READ and WRITE agent-assigned siblings on case_task use
      <advanced>true</advanced> so the platform invokes their CDATA scripted
      condition that dereferences current.case via getRefRecord() and
      evaluates "parentCase.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() OR
      parentCase.assigned_group contains current user." That predicate
      cannot be evaluated at create time because:
        1. No `current` record exists yet - the row is being inserted at
           the moment the ACL fires. The platform binds `current` to a
           freshly-instantiated record skeleton with the caller's POSTed
           field values; calling getRefRecord() against a not-yet-saved
           reference field on that skeleton returns an unstable / empty
           result that produces false positives or false negatives.
        2. Even if `current.case` were already populated (e.g., the form
           pre-fills it from the parent case context the user navigated
           from), checking parent-case assignment at create-time would
           merely duplicate the parent-case READ ACL the platform has
           ALREADY enforced (the user could not have opened the parent
           case to start a related-list create unless the case-level
           agent_assigned read ACL had already permitted it). Re-running
           the same predicate at task-create time is redundant.
        3. Per the AAP design pattern in Section 0.4.3 the "Assigned only"
           predicate is reserved for read/write ACLs; create is a binary
           role check.
      Consequences of <advanced>false</advanced>:
        - <condition/>  is evaluated as an empty encoded query (no row
                        filter; permits the request).
        - <script/>     is NOT evaluated (the platform skips it when
                        advanced=false).
        - <roles>       remains the sole admission gate: callers holding
                        x_[scope]_case_agent are granted create; callers
                        without the role are denied.
      This is the standard ServiceNow pattern for "any role member can
      perform this operation, no per-row predicate" and matches the agent
      prompt's "create has no condition" rule verbatim.

    Why creation is unconditional and what governs the created row afterward:
      Pre-creation there is no record to evaluate against - any "row-level"
      check on parent-case assignment is logically impossible at this
      stage of the request lifecycle. Once the task record is inserted,
      downstream access is governed by:
        (a) The read/write _agent_assigned task-level ACLs (siblings of
            this file), which restrict the creating agent's subsequent
            visibility of and edits to the freshly-created task to the
            rows where the PARENT CASE has the agent as assigned_agent
            or as a member of assigned_group. This means an agent CAN
            insert a task pointing at any case row, but if they pick a
            case to which they have no assignment, the very next read of
            that task (e.g., upon redirect to the task form after submit)
            will be denied by the task-level read ACL - producing a
            "you-just-created-it-but-cannot-see-it" outcome that is
            harmless and self-correcting.
        (b) The case-table read/write _agent_assigned ACLs (siblings of
            this file at one level higher), which already restrict which
            cases an agent can OPEN to begin a related-list create from.
            In normal operational flow the agent only ever sees a "Create
            related task" UI action on cases they already have access to;
            the case-table ACLs therefore implicitly funnel all new task
            creates onto cases the agent is allowed to act on.
        (c) Mandatory-field constraints declared on the dictionary
            entries (../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_task_*.xml): per AAP
            Section 0.5.7 every task field except `type` is mandatory, so
            even if the agent attempts to insert a degenerate task row to
            probe the ACL, the platform rejects the row at the schema
            layer before the ACL evaluator returns success.
      In short: an agent CAN create a task but cannot weaponize the
      privilege to inject tasks onto unassigned cases, because the
      platform's standard navigation surface only exposes the create
      action from cases the agent already has access to, and any
      out-of-band attempt to insert a task on an unassigned case results
      in an immediately-invisible row with no operational utility.

    Why a separate file per role (instead of one create ACL with both roles):
      ServiceNow allows multiple roles in a single <roles> field as a
      comma-separated list, and that pattern technically also satisfies
      the AAP. However, the established convention in this Update Set
      (and in industry practice for scoped applications) is one ACL
      record per (table, operation, role) triple. Reasons:
        - Single-responsibility: each ACL record encodes exactly one
          authorization fact; if the AAP later removes case_agent's
          create privilege on case_task (e.g., to enforce a stricter
          intake-via-portal-only policy), the change is a single-file
          deletion with no risk of accidentally also revoking
          case_manager's create privilege.
        - Auditability: the file inventory under ../acl/ becomes a
          self-documenting matrix - the presence or absence of a file
          named x_[scope]_<table>_<operation>_<role>.xml is the answer
          to "does role X have privilege Y on table Z?".
        - Update Set diff clarity: when the Update Set is re-imported on
          a fresh PDI, each ACL is a discrete row in the preview screen,
          making it easy to spot that case_agent's create privilege was
          installed (alongside case_manager's) versus a single combined
          row that would obscure the role membership.
      The companion ../acl/x_[scope]_case_task_create_manager.xml file
      authors the case_manager half of the Create=Yes pair using the
      same per-role-per-operation pattern.

    Mirror relationship to ../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_agent.xml:
      This file is the case_task-table analog of the agent-create ACL
      already authored for the case table at
      ../acl/x_[scope]_case_create_agent.xml. The ONLY differences
      between that file and this one are:
        - <name>           x_[scope]_case_task   (vs x_[scope]_case)
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_[scope]_case_task.create.case_agent")
                                                 (vs MD5("x_[scope]_case.create.case_agent"))
        - <sys_name>       x_[scope]_case_task   (vs x_[scope]_case)
        - <sys_update_name> sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_task_create_agent
                                                 (vs sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_create_agent)
        - <description>    references the case_task table semantic
      All other fields (active, admin_overrides, advanced, condition,
      operation, roles, script, sys_class_name, sys_created_by,
      sys_policy, sys_scope, sys_package, type, audit timestamps) are
      byte-for-byte identical so that the agent's create privilege is
      uniformly unconditional across both the case and case_task tables
      in the scoped application as the AAP matrix mandates.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the
        property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, an
        "agent-equivalent" role would have been associated with privilege
        identifiers such as `acm-task-create` or `acm-task-add`, and
        those privilege strings would have been resolved at runtime
        against URL-method bindings declared in
        ApplicationPluginPrivilegesConfig.getApplicationPluginsPrivileges()
        via AcmPluginUrlPrivilege. The ServiceNow target replaces this
        bifurcated model (declarative privilege list + imperative URL-
        binding) with a single declarative scoped record-level ACL: this
        XML record IS the (case_agent, CREATE on TASK) cell of that
        conceptual map.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`,
        plus the role-name normalization step that uppercased the role,
        replaced whitespace with underscores, replaced periods with
        double-underscores, and prepended the `ROLE_` prefix from
        RolePrivilegesConstants). All of this Java service surface is
        replaced in the ServiceNow target by the platform's built-in
        sys_security_acl evaluator and by static role names declared in
        scope-prefixed sys_user_role records (the case_agent role is
        declared in ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml; this
        ACL references it by literal name in the <roles> field). The
        role-name-normalization step in particular is replaced by the
        scoped-application convention of using literal scope-prefixed
        role names (e.g., x_[scope]_case_agent) directly in the <roles>
        field below - no `ROLE_` prefix is prepended, no case folding
        occurs, and the role name is treated as an opaque identifier
        resolved by name against the OOB sys_user_role table.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_[scope] scope (sys_scope = x_[scope], sys_package =
        x_[scope]). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_[scope]_case_task (NOT the OOB
        `task` table or any other global table), and <roles> references
        the scoped role x_[scope]_case_agent. Per AAP Section 0.3.2
        "Global scope changes of any kind" are explicitly prohibited.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id>
        below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of the
        canonical identifier "x_[scope]_case_task.create.case_agent", a
        stable key for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to
        any other record. Computing the sys_id deterministically
        guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh
        PDIs and round-trip Update Set previews per AAP Section 0.7.3
        Gate 7.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_[scope]_case_task`
        with NO dot. ServiceNow's create operation has no concept of
        "create this specific column" - field-level ACLs apply only to
        read/write/none. The <type>record</type> field below confirms
        this is a row-level (table-level) ACL, not a UI/REST/SOAP-
        flavored ACL.
      - Operation = create: corresponds exactly to the "Create = Yes"
        cell in the AAP matrix for the case_agent role on the case_task
        table.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or seed
        scoped data (per AAP Section 0.7.4 the seed_demo_data.js script
        seeds tasks under the platform's elevated context). It does NOT
        widen case_agent privileges - case_agents without admin still
        see exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.
      - advanced = false: see "Why advanced=false" rationale above. The
        platform skips the empty <script/> body entirely.
      - condition (empty): the <condition/> encoded-query field is empty;
        no row-level filter applies (and none is meaningful pre-insert).
      - script (empty): the <script/> field is empty; the platform skips
        it because advanced=false.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped app
          record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_[scope]")
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case_task.xml (resolves
          <name>x_[scope]_case_task</name>)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_[scope]_case_agent.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles> by role name)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
          (the demo agent's create access during round-trip
          verification depends on this ACL being applied first)
        - ../seed-data/tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml (demo
          tasks inserted by the seed pass need this ACL in place if any
          seed runs under the demo agent's identity context; the
          seed_demo_data.js script itself runs as admin so
          admin_overrides bypasses this ACL during seeding, but post-
          seed agent-side smoke tests against the demo dataset depend
          on this ACL being applied)

    The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim per AAP
    convention (Section 0.7.2 "Scoped-namespace-only constraint"); the
    Personal Developer Instance auto-assigns the actual concrete scope
    id at App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-
    time renaming propagates consistently across all bracketed
    placeholders in this artifact. The deterministic sys_id below is
    computed against the `[scope]` literal and remains stable across
    re-imports onto fresh PDIs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Allows users with the x_[scope]_case_agent role to create case_task records.</description>
        <name>x_[scope]_case_task</name>
        <operation>create</operation>
        <roles>x_[scope]_case_agent</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>e0d5a22fa8de097d5b478125eb6dfc67</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_[scope]_case_task</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_[scope]_case_task_create_agent</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
